    "content": {
      "language": "en",
      "problem_latex": "Given: $a-b\\textgreater a$ and $a+b\\textless b$. Which of the following must be true?~\\uline{~~~~~~~~~~}~  $I$. $a b$ is negative  $II$. $a+b$ is negative  $III$. $a-b$ is negative\n(A) I$ only\n(B) I$ and $III$ only\n(C) II$ only\n(D) I$, $II$, $III",
      "problem_plain": "Given: a-b a and a+b b . Which of the following must be true?~ ~~~~~~~~~~ ~ I . a b is negative II . a+b is negative III . a-b is negative (A) I only (B) I and III only (C) II only (D) I , II , III",
      "solution_latex": "$a-b\\textgreater a$ then $b\\textless0$  $a+b\\textless b$ then $a\\textless0$.  So both $a$ and $b$ are negative. $I$ is false, since the product will be positive. $II$ is true since the sum of two negative numbers is negative. $III$ is false because if $a=-1$ and $b=-2$ then $a-b$ is positive. Only $II$ is true.",
      "solution_plain": "a-b a then b 0 a+b b then a 0 . So both a and b are negative. I is false, since the product will be positive. II is true since the sum of two negative numbers is negative. III is false because if a=-1 and b=-2 then a-b is positive. Only II is true."
    },
    "answer": {
      "final_raw": "II$ only",
      "final_normalized": "II$ only",
      "candidates": [
        "C",
        "II$ only"
      ],
